"""
mkt-original | leviticus | ch 16-18
Yom Kippur (16), blood prohibition and life-in-blood axiom (17), sexual ethics code (18).
Key terms: kapporet (atonement cover/mercy seat), azazel (16:8,10), kipper (atone),
Shabbat Shabbaton (complete rest), inui nefesh (self-denial), nefesh habasar badam
(life of flesh in blood), se'irim (goat-demons), vaḥai bahem (live by them — 18:5),
erva (nakedness), to'evah (abomination), karet (cutting off), Molech.
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-leviticus-16-18.py
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

LEVITICUS = {
  "16": {
    "1": "<p>The Yom Kippur legislation is grounded in the death of Nadab and Abihu (Lev 10:1-2), who entered YHWH's presence without authorization. The historical reference (<em>aḥarei mot shney bnei Aharon</em>, 'after the death of the two sons of Aaron') sets the chapter in the aftermath of a catastrophic priestly failure. Yom Kippur is the divinely-given solution: an annual, authorized, highly regulated pathway into the divine presence, structured to prevent the death that comes from unauthorized approach.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>al-yavo bekhol-et el-haqqodesh</strong>: 'He shall not come at any time he pleases into the holy place.' The restriction is absolute — no impromptu entry. <strong>lifnei hakapporet</strong>: 'before the <em>kapporet</em>' — the atonement cover over the ark. <em>Kapporet</em> (from <em>kipper</em>, to atone/cover) is the gold lid of the ark where YHWH's presence was localized. The LXX renders it <em>hilasterion</em> (place of propitiation/mercy seat), the same term Paul applies to Christ in Rom 3:25. The prohibition on casual entry is the negative premise of the entire Yom Kippur system.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>bezot yavo Aharon el-haqqodesh</strong>: 'In this way Aaron shall enter the holy place.' The emphatic demonstrative <em>bezot</em> (in this / by this) marks the entry protocol as the sole legitimate pathway. The two animals: <em>par ben-baqar</em> (young bull) for the sin offering (<em>ḥatta't</em>) for Aaron's own sin, and a ram for the burnt offering (<em>olah</em>). The priest must address his own impurity before mediating for the people — a point Hebrews exploits to contrast Christ, who had no sin of his own (Heb 7:27).</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>ketonet-bad qodesh yilbash</strong>: 'He shall put on the holy linen tunic.' On Yom Kippur the high priest exchanges his normal elaborate golden vestments (Exod 28) for simple white linen — <em>bad</em> (linen) repeated four times in this verse. The linen is white (<em>lavan</em>), associated with purity. The high priest enters the holy of holies not in his symbols of status but in symbols of purity — a reversal of normal priestly display. The four linen garments all belong to YHWH (<em>bigdei qodesh</em>, holy garments).</p>",
    "5": "<p>From the congregation: two male goats (<em>se'irei izzim</em>) for the sin offering and one ram for the burnt offering. The two goats are a single sin offering taken together — they function as a paired unit representing the two aspects of atonement: blood-payment (the slaughtered goat) and removal (the scapegoat). One offering, two mechanisms. This two-part structure will be explained through vv. 15-22.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>vehiqriv Aharon et-par haḥatta't asher-lo vekhipper ba'ado uvead beito</strong>: 'Aaron shall offer the bull of his sin offering and make atonement for himself and his household.' The sequential structure requires the priest's own atonement first — he cannot mediate for others until he himself has been cleansed. <em>Bead beito</em> (for his household) includes his wife and all dependent family members. The necessity of priestly self-atonement is the main contrast point of Heb 7:27: 'He has no need, like those high priests, to offer sacrifices daily, first for his own sins and then for those of the people.'</p>",
    "7": "<p>The two goats are presented together at the sanctuary entrance. The paired presentation before YHWH is necessary before lot-casting — both goats belong to the ritual simultaneously; they are not yet differentiated. The structural parallel with the two birds in the leper's cleansing (Lev 14:4-7) is noted by later interpreters: one is killed, one released; both together represent cleansing.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>venatan Aharon al-shnei hase'irim goralot</strong>: 'Aaron shall cast lots over the two goats.' <em>Goralot</em> (lots) — the method is not described precisely; later tradition (Mishnah Yoma) used two inscribed gold tablets. The critical term: <strong>azazel</strong>. This is the most debated term in Leviticus. Three main interpretations: (1) a place name ('land of removal/desolation'); (2) a compound meaning 'goat of removal' or 'complete removal' (<em>ez-azal</em>); (3) a supernatural entity — a wilderness demon or fallen angel to whom the goat is dispatched (supported by 1 Enoch, Dead Sea Scrolls, and the parallel with goat-demons in 17:7). The MKT renders <em>azazel</em> as a proper name, leaving the ambiguity intact.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The goat assigned to YHWH by lot becomes the sin offering — it is slaughtered, its blood brought inside the veil. This is the propitiatory goat: its blood atones in the sanctuary, cleansing the holy place from accumulated Israelite impurity. The lot procedure ensures that neither goat is pre-selected by human choice — the assignment is YHWH's own determination.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>veha-sa'ir asher ala alav hagoral la'aza'zel ya'amod-ḥai lifnei YHWH lekapper alav</strong>: 'The goat on which the lot for Azazel fell shall be presented alive before YHWH to make atonement over it.' The live goat's function is also atonement (<em>kipper</em>) — but its mechanism is different: not blood-sprinkling but confession and removal. It is first presented before YHWH (legitimizing the ritual), then used for confession, then released. The word <em>ḥai</em> (alive) emphasizes that this goat does not die in the ritual; its death outside the camp (or at the cliff, per later tradition) is incidental to its function.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Aaron slaughters his bull first — before the people's goat — demonstrating the sequential logic: self-atonement must precede intercession. <em>Vekhipper ba'ado uvead beito</em> (and he shall make atonement for himself and his household) is repeated from v. 6, reinforcing the priority of priestly cleansing. The blood of Aaron's bull will be used inside the holy of holies (v. 14).</p>",
    "12": "<p><strong>veleqaḥ melo-hammaḥtah gaḥalei-esh me'al hamizbeaḥ</strong>: 'He shall take a censer full of burning coals from the altar.' The incense censer is the high priest's shield for entering the holy of holies: he carries coals from the bronze altar and two handfuls of finely ground fragrant incense (<em>qetoret sammim daqah</em>). The incense cloud (<em>anan heqetoret</em>) will cover the <em>kapporet</em>, protecting the priest from seeing YHWH directly. The smoke is protective, not merely ceremonial — <em>velo yamut</em> (and he shall not die) is the goal.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>venatan et-haqetoret al-ha'esh lifnei YHWH vekissa anan-haqetoret et-hakapporet</strong>: 'He shall put the incense on the fire before YHWH so that the cloud of incense covers the atonement cover.' The incense cloud functions as a veil between the priest's sight and the divine presence localized at the <em>kapporet</em>. The theology: YHWH's presence is genuinely located here, but direct exposure is lethal. The incense mediates access. Later tradition (Mishnah Yoma 5:1) preserves Pharisaic debate over whether the incense should be lit before or after entering the veil — a halakhic dispute reflecting the verse's precise sequence.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>velakaḥ middam hapar vehizza beetzba'o al-pnei hakapporet qedmah</strong>: 'He shall take some of the bull's blood and sprinkle it with his finger on the front of the atonement cover eastward.' The blood is applied to the <em>kapporet</em> (the divine throne) directly. The direction: <em>qedmah</em> (eastward/on the east face) — once on the face of the <em>kapporet</em> itself, then seven times before it on the floor. Seven is the completion number (Gen 1). The blood-sprinkling on and before the <em>kapporet</em> is the central act of the entire Yom Kippur ritual — it is where atonement happens at its most concentrated point.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The same blood-sprinkling procedure is repeated with the people's goat blood inside the holy of holies. Aaron sprinkles bull blood (for his own sin) and goat blood (for the people's sin) on and before the <em>kapporet</em> in the same sequence. The doubled application — priest's blood then people's blood — makes Yom Kippur atonement comprehensive: both priesthood and congregation are cleansed from sin accumulated during the year.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>vekhipper al-haqqodesh mitum'ot bnei Yisrael umippish'eihem lekhol-ḥatotam</strong>: 'He shall make atonement for the holy place because of the uncleannesses of the Israelites and because of their transgressions, for all their sins.' Three categories are distinguished: <em>tumot</em> (ritual uncleannesses — the accumulated impurity from birth, death, bodily flows), <em>psha'im</em> (willful transgressions/rebellions), <em>ḥatot</em> (sins generally). The holy place itself has been contaminated by Israel's sins even though they never entered it — the sanctuary absorbs impurity from the camp. Yom Kippur cleanses the sanctuary as much as the people.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>vekhol-adam lo-yihyeh be'ohel mo'ed bevo'o lekapper baqqodesh</strong>: 'No person shall be in the tent of meeting when he enters to make atonement in the holy place.' Total isolation of the high priest during the inner-sanctuary work. This is the moment of greatest solemnity — the entire community waits outside while the single mediator stands before YHWH. The exclusion of 'all persons' (<em>kol-adam</em>) reinforces the uniqueness of the high-priestly role. The NT will use this structure: Christ enters the true holy of holies alone, as the sole mediator (1 Tim 2:5; Heb 9:7, 11-12).</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>veyatsa el-hamizbeaḥ asher lifnei YHWH vekhipper alav</strong>: 'He shall come out to the altar that is before YHWH and make atonement for it.' Having cleansed the inner sanctuary, the high priest moves outward: first the altar of incense (implied), then the bronze altar. The outward movement is spatially significant — atonement radiates from the most holy place outward through the entire sanctuary complex. Blood from both animals is mixed and applied to the four horns of the altar.</p>",
    "19": "<p><strong>vehizza alav min-hadam beetzba'o sheva pe'amim</strong>: 'He shall sprinkle some of the blood on it with his finger seven times.' The sevenfold sprinkling (also at v. 14) is the completion number — seven applications ensure comprehensive cleansing. <em>Veteherhu veqiddesho mitum'ot bnei Yisrael</em> (cleansing it and consecrating it from the uncleannesses of the Israelites): the altar's dual state change — from impure to clean, from ordinary to consecrated — accomplished by blood application.</p>",
    "20": "<p>The transition from sanctuary-cleansing to scapegoat: the live goat is now summoned. The sequencing is deliberate — the sanctuary must be cleansed first; only then is the confession ritual performed over the live goat. The two mechanisms address different aspects: the blood deals with impurity in the sanctuary; the scapegoat deals with iniquity symbolically removed from the community.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>vesomakh Aharon et-shetei yadav al-rosh hasa'ir haḥai vehitvaddah alav</strong>: 'Aaron shall lay both his hands on the head of the live goat and confess over it all the iniquities of the Israelites.' The <em>semikah</em> here uses both hands (<em>shetei yadav</em>) — the intensive form, reserving full weight and identification for this act. The verbal confession (<em>viddui</em>) spoken over the goat is the mechanism of transfer: the named iniquities of Israel are laid onto the goat. <em>Kol-avonot bnei Yisrael</em> (all the iniquities of the Israelites) + <em>kol-pisha'eihem lekhol-ḥatotam</em> (all their transgressions, all their sins) — the triple formula covers everything.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>venasa hasa'ir alav et-kol-avonotam el-erets gezerah</strong>: 'The goat shall carry all their iniquities to a land cut off.' <em>Nasa</em> (to carry/bear) is the same verb used for bearing sin throughout the OT and in Isa 53:12 (<em>vehu ḥet-rabbim nasa</em>, 'he bore the sins of many'). <em>Erets gezerah</em> (land cut off / desolate/isolated land) — the goat goes to a place of complete separation. The removal is spatial and irreversible: the community's sins go away, carried by a living being, to a place from which there is no return.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Aaron re-enters the tent of meeting to remove the Yom Kippur linen garments and leave them inside — they are too holy for ordinary use and cannot re-enter the camp. He then bathes and puts on his regular high-priestly vestments before offering the burnt offerings. The change of garments marks the transition from the extraordinary (holy of holies entry) back to the ordinary high-priestly ministry.</p>",
    "24": "<p>Aaron bathes in the holy place, dresses in his regular garments, and goes out to offer his own and the people's burnt offerings (<em>olot</em>). The burnt offerings (one ram each for Aaron and the congregation) complete the Yom Kippur complex — the sin offerings cleanse; the burnt offerings restore the relationship and express total dedication. The sequence: cleansing → restoration.</p>",
    "25": "<p>The fat (<em>ḥelev</em>) of the sin-offering animals is burned on the altar — the portion belonging to YHWH. Even on Yom Kippur, the standard rule that fat belongs to YHWH is maintained (Lev 3:16-17). The burning of fat is a <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ</em> (pleasing aroma) offering even when the main blood-work has been unusual.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The man who led the scapegoat away (<em>meshalaḥ hasa'ir la'aza'zel</em>) becomes ritually impure through the act — he has been the vehicle by which Israel's sins were conveyed outside the camp. He must wash his clothes and bathe before returning. The impurity is not moral guilt but ritual contamination acquired by handling the sin-laden goat.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The carcasses of the bull and the goat (whose blood was brought into the holy place) must be taken outside the camp and burned — skin, flesh, and dung. The fire outside the camp (<em>miḥuts lammaḥaneh</em>) is the disposal mechanism for the most holy sin-offering animals whose blood entered the inner sanctuary. This rule is cited by Heb 13:11-12 as the type of Christ suffering 'outside the gate.'</p>",
    "28": "<p>The man who burns the carcasses also becomes unclean and must wash and bathe. Three people acquire impurity through Yom Kippur rituals: (1) the scapegoat handler (v. 26), (2) the carcass-burner (v. 28), and (3) implicitly Aaron himself requires bathing (v. 24). The entire ritual generates contagion in the participants — the mediation of sin is not cost-free even for those facilitating atonement.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>vehayetah lachem leḥuqqat olam baḥodesh hashvei'i be'asor laḥodesh te'annu et-nafshoteikhem</strong>: 'This shall be a statute forever for you: on the tenth day of the seventh month you shall practice self-denial.' <em>Inui nefesh</em> (affliction/self-denial of soul) is the biblical prescription for Yom Kippur fasting — the noun <em>innui</em> (affliction) from the verb <em>anah</em> (to afflict/humble). Rabbinic tradition identified five deprivations: no eating, no drinking, no bathing, no anointing, no marital relations. <em>Leḥuqqat olam</em> (a statute forever) marks this as a permanent covenant obligation.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>ki vayom hazeh yekhapper aleikhem letaher etkhem mikol ḥatoteikhem lifnei YHWH titharu</strong>: 'For on this day atonement shall be made for you to cleanse you; from all your sins before YHWH you shall be clean.' The climactic statement of Yom Kippur's purpose: comprehensive cleansing (<em>taher</em>) from all sins. <em>Lifnei YHWH</em> (before YHWH) — the cleansing is not merely social or psychological but covenantal and relational, occurring in YHWH's presence. The passive <em>titharu</em> (you shall be clean) emphasizes that cleansing is something done to Israel, not accomplished by Israel's effort.</p>",
    "31": "<p><strong>Shabbat Shabbaton hi lachem</strong>: 'It is a Shabbat of complete rest for you.' <em>Shabbat Shabbaton</em> is the superlative construction (Sabbath of Sabbaths = the ultimate/complete Sabbath) — the highest intensity of the Sabbath principle. Yom Kippur is the only day in the Torah calendar given this designation, shared only with the seventh-year land sabbath (Lev 25:4) and one other observance. The phrase combines the annual atonement calendar with the weekly rest rhythm, marking it as a peak moment in Israel's entire temporal structure.</p>",
    "32": "<p>The law applies to any legitimately anointed and ordained high priest, not only to Aaron personally — <em>asher-yimshaḥ oto vaasher yemale yadav</em> (who is anointed and whose hand is filled) = the full ordination formula. This forward-looking clause establishes Yom Kippur as an ongoing priestly institution, not a one-time event tied to Aaron's personal ministry.</p>",
    "33": "<p>The comprehensive scope of Yom Kippur atonement: the holy sanctuary (<em>miqdash haqqodesh</em>), the tent of meeting, the altar, the priests, and all the congregation of Israel (<em>kol-am haqqahal</em>). Atonement radiates outward from the holy of holies through every layer of the sanctuary and community. No part of Israel's covenant structure is excluded from the annual cleansing.</p>",
    "34": "<p><strong>lekhapper al-bnei Yisrael mikol-ḥatotam aḥat bashanah</strong>: 'to make atonement for Israel from all their sins once a year.' <em>Aḥat bashanah</em> (once a year) — the limitation is the key theological datum exploited by Hebrews: the annual repetition proves that Yom Kippur could not achieve permanent removal of sin (Heb 10:1-3). If the sacrifice had accomplished its goal, the worshippers would have been cleansed once for all and the annual ritual would have been unnecessary. The repetition is the system's built-in indicator that it was provisional, designed to point forward to a once-for-all (<em>ephapax</em>) sacrifice.</p>"
  },
  "17": {
    "1": "<p>Standard address formula. Chapter 17 opens the Holiness Code's initial layer — the blood laws that regulate all animal slaughter and consumption. The broad addressee (Aaron, sons, all Israel) signals a universal obligation extending beyond the sanctuary to all Israelite life.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The law extends to 'all the people of Israel' (<em>kol-bnei Yisrael</em>) — not merely the priests — and specifically names the act of slaughtering (<em>yishḥat</em>) livestock. The law governs not just ritual sacrifice but ordinary butchering: in the wilderness period, no animal may be slaughtered outside the sanctuary.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>ish ish mibbeit Yisrael asher yishḥat</strong>: 'any man of Israel who slaughters.' The repeated <em>ish ish</em> (man, man = anyone/whoever) is the legal universalizing formula in Leviticus. The three animals: <em>shor</em> (ox/bull), <em>keves</em> (lamb), <em>ez</em> (goat) — the domesticated animals that can be offered sacrificially. The rule applies regardless of location: inside or outside the camp.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>vedam yiḥasheiv laish hahu dam shafakh</strong>: 'blood shall be reckoned to that man — he has shed blood.' Anyone who slaughters without bringing the animal to the sanctuary entrance is guilty of <em>shefikh dam</em> (bloodshed) — treated like murder. This is because unauthorized slaughter severs the connection between killing and atonement that the sanctuary system maintains. <em>Venikh'rat haish hahu miqqerev ammo</em>: 'that man shall be cut off from among his people' — the <em>karet</em> penalty, which represents the most severe divine punishment short of execution.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The purpose of centralizing slaughter at the sanctuary: <em>lema'an asher yavi'u bnei Yisrael et-ziḥeihem</em> (so that the Israelites may bring their sacrifices). The word <em>ziḥeihem</em> (their sacrifices, from <em>zevaḥ</em>) refers to what they were previously offering in the open field — slaughter-meals that had a quasi-sacrificial character. By requiring all such slaughter to come to the sanctuary, YHWH absorbs and Torahizes the universal human impulse to mark killing with ritual.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The priest throws (<em>zaraq</em>) the blood against the altar — the verb is distinctive, suggesting a vigorous throwing action rather than careful application. The fat is burned as a <em>reiaḥ niḥoaḥ</em> (pleasing aroma). By requiring all slaughter to flow through this mechanism, every meat meal in Israel becomes a form of communion with YHWH.</p>",
    "7": "<p><strong>velo-yizbeḥu od et-ziḥeihem lasse'irim asher hem zonim aḥarei-hem</strong>: 'They shall no longer sacrifice their offerings to the goat-demons (<em>se'irim</em>) after whom they have been whoring.' <em>Se'irim</em> (goat-demons, sg. <em>sa'ir</em>) — the term for the semi-divine wilderness beings associated with arid places and disorder (Isa 13:21, 34:14). The use of <em>zonim</em> (whoring/prostituting) for idolatry is the standard prophetic language for covenant unfaithfulness. The law addresses a real syncretistic practice in Israel's past.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The law extends to resident aliens (<em>ger</em>) — the foreigner living among Israel is subject to the same slaughter centralization rule. This is a recurring pattern in the Holiness Code: the resident alien is included in Israel's covenant obligations, not just Israel's covenant privileges. <em>Ger haggur betokham</em> (the alien who sojourns among them) cannot maintain a parallel pagan sacrificial system.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The penalty for unauthorized sacrifice (even of permitted animals) is <em>karet</em> — being cut off from the people. This applies equally to native Israelite and resident alien. The equivalence of native and alien under the blood laws reflects the Holiness Code's consistent expansion of covenant obligations beyond ethnic Israel.</p>",
    "10": "<p><strong>veish ish mibbeit Yisrael umin-hager hagar betokham asher yokhal kol-dam</strong>: 'any man of Israel or resident alien who eats any blood.' The blood prohibition is broader than the slaughter law: it applies to any blood in any form. The penalty: <em>unatati fanai banaefesh ha'okhelat et-hadam</em> (I will set my face against the person who eats blood and cut him off) — YHWH's own personal attention is the enforcement mechanism. This is the most direct form of divine sanction in Leviticus, reserved for fundamental violations.</p>",
    "11": "<p><strong>ki nefesh habasar badam hi vaani netatihu lachem al-hamizbeaḥ lekapper al-nafshoteikhem ki-hadam hu banaefesh yekhapper</strong>: 'For the life of the flesh is in the blood, and I have given it to you on the altar to make atonement for your lives, for it is the blood that makes atonement by the life.' The theological axiom of all sacrificial atonement. <em>Nefesh</em> (life/soul) of the flesh is <em>badam</em> (in the blood) — not that blood = soul, but that blood is the carrier/bearer of the life-principle. YHWH has specifically designated (<em>netatihu</em>, I have given it) blood for altar use — sacrifice is not a human invention but a divine appointment. The exchange mechanism: blood (= life) offered for the life (<em>nefesh</em>) of the worshipper. The verse is quoted or applied in Heb 9:22 ('without the shedding of blood there is no forgiveness').</p>",
    "12": "<p>Summary restatement of the blood prohibition with the same universalizing <em>ish ish</em> formula. The double prohibition (no native, no alien) emphasizes that the blood taboo transcends ethnic and covenant boundaries — it reflects something about blood's intrinsic association with life that makes consumption an offense against the life-principle itself.</p>",
    "13": "<p><strong>asher yatsud tseid ḥayyah o-oph asher ye'akhel</strong>: 'who hunts a game animal or bird that may be eaten.' Game animals (hunted rather than domesticated) are subject to a special blood rule: since their blood cannot be brought to the altar (they are not slaughter animals), it must be poured out and covered with earth (<em>ve'ikissahu be'afar</em>). <em>Shafakh dam</em> (poured out) + <em>kissa</em> (covered) — the blood is given back to the earth, acknowledging that it belongs to YHWH even when it cannot go to the altar.</p>",
    "14": "<p><strong>ki nefesh kol-basar damo venafshoto hu</strong>: 'the life of every creature — its blood is its life.' Restatement of the v. 11 principle applied to game animals: the blood-prohibition follows from the blood-life equation. The phrase <em>kol-asher yokhlenu yikkareth</em> (whoever eats it shall be cut off) applies the <em>karet</em> penalty uniformly across all animal categories.</p>",
    "15": "<p><strong>vekhol-nefesh asher tokhal nevelah uterefa ba'eziret uvagger</strong>: 'Every person — native or alien — who eats an animal that died naturally or was torn.' <em>Nevelah</em> (naturally dead) and <em>terefa</em> (torn by wild animals) — the two categories of non-slaughtered death. Eating them generates ritual impurity requiring clothes-washing and bathing; the person remains unclean until evening. This is a graduated penalty compared to the <em>karet</em> of v. 14 — eating from natural death is less severe than eating blood, but still requires purification.</p>",
    "16": "<p><strong>ve'im lo yekhabbeis veguffo lo yirḥats venasa avono</strong>: 'if he does not wash his clothes and does not bathe his body, he shall bear his iniquity.' The responsibility for purification lies with the individual: failure to perform the ritual washing does not remove the impurity but makes the person culpable for remaining in an impure state. <em>Venasa avono</em> (he shall bear his iniquity) — the language of personal moral accountability applied to a ritual-purity context.</p>"
  },
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>Standard address formula opening the Holiness Code proper. Chapter 18 begins with a framing preamble (vv. 1-5) before listing the sexual prohibitions. The placement of the sexual ethics code immediately after the blood/sacrifice laws (ch. 17) signals that purity of body, like purity of sacrifice, is part of the holiness program.</p>",
    "2": "<p><strong>ani YHWH Eloheikhem</strong>: 'I am YHWH your God.' This self-identification formula appears throughout chs. 18-26 as a refrain anchoring each law in YHWH's own identity and covenant relationship. The laws are not arbitrary rules but expressions of who YHWH is and what the covenant relationship requires. The formula occurs 48 times in Leviticus, clustering in the Holiness Code.</p>",
    "3": "<p><strong>kema'asei erets-Mitsrayim asher yeshavtem bah lo ta'asu ukema'asei erets-Kena'an</strong>: 'You shall not do as they do in the land of Egypt, where you lived, and you shall not do as they do in the land of Canaan.' Israel's sexual ethics are defined negatively against both past (Egypt) and future (Canaan) environments. The logic: Israel is not to assimilate to surrounding cultures. The double prohibition creates Israel's ethical identity as a people genuinely distinct from both its origin and its destination.</p>",
    "4": "<p><strong>et-mishpatai ta'asu ve'et-ḥuqqotai tishemru lalekhet bahem</strong>: 'Keep my rules and observe my statutes and walk in them.' Two legal categories: <em>mishpatim</em> (judgments/rules — laws whose rationale is accessible to reason) and <em>ḥuqqot</em> (statutes — laws whose rationale is YHWH's sovereign decree). Both require obedience; the distinction is not between easier and harder laws but between transparent and opaque ones. <em>Lalekhet bahem</em> (to walk in them) — the covenant life as a path, not a set of discrete acts.</p>",
    "5": "<p><strong>ushmartem et-ḥuqqotai ve'et-mishpatai asher ya'aseh otam ha'adam vaḥai bahem</strong>: 'Keep my statutes and my rules; the person who does them shall live by them.' <em>Vaḥai bahem</em> (and he shall live by them) — the life-promise of the covenant commands. Paul quotes this verse in Gal 3:12 and Rom 10:5 to distinguish law-observance from faith: the law promises life to those who <em>do</em> all its commands; faith promises life to those who trust. Paul's point is not that the law was wrong in its life-promise but that no one fully does all its commands — only Christ did. Lev 18:5 is the positive statement of what covenant obedience achieves; Gal 3:10-13 is Paul's analysis of why it cannot be achieved without Christ.</p>",
    "6": "<p><strong>kol-ish ish el-kol-she'er besaro lo tiqrevu legallot erva</strong>: 'None of you shall approach any close relative to uncover nakedness.' <em>She'er basar</em> (close relative, lit. 'flesh relative') — the term for those sharing kinship bonds. <em>Erva</em> (nakedness/genitalia) — the consistent term throughout ch. 18 for the sexual domain. The root <em>glh</em> (to uncover/expose) when used with <em>erva</em> means to engage in sexual relations. <em>Lo tiqrevu</em> (you shall not approach) uses the same approach-language as the sanctuary access rules — sexual impropriety violates sacred space.</p>",
    "7": "<p>First specific prohibition: father's sexual partner (mother). <em>Erva avikha ve'erva immekha</em> (the nakedness of your father and the nakedness of your mother) — the mother's body is described as 'your father's nakedness,' reflecting the marital one-flesh bond: to approach her is to violate your father. The double identification (she is your mother; she is your father's nakedness) closes both possible loopholes.</p>",
    "8": "<p><strong>erva eshet avikha lo tegalle</strong>: 'You shall not uncover the nakedness of your father's wife.' This covers step-mothers and other wives beyond one's birth mother — the prohibition extends to anyone in the role of father's wife. <em>Erva avikha hi</em> (it is your father's nakedness) — the same logic as v. 7: the wife's body participates in the marital bond's sanctity.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Prohibitions on half-sisters (paternal and maternal, born inside or outside the family household). The comprehensive listing ('whether born in the house or elsewhere') closes kinship loopholes — adoption, mixed family structures, and children born outside wedlock are all included. The Holiness Code's sexual legislation is notably more comprehensive than earlier prohibitions in the Torah.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Granddaughters (son's daughter or daughter's daughter) are prohibited. <em>Ki ervatekha henah</em> (for they are your own nakedness) — the granddaughter participates in the grandfather's identity through descent, making incest a form of self-violation. The kinship logic: you are diminished by what happens to those who share your flesh.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The daughter of one's father's wife (step-sister through the father) — 'begotten by your father; she is your sister.' The prohibition covers relationships that might be considered distant enough to be permitted in some ancient Near Eastern contexts (e.g., Abraham's marriage to Sarah, who was his half-sister, Gen 20:12, which predates this legislation).</p>",
    "12": "<p>Father's sister — <em>she'er avikha hi</em> (she is your father's blood relative). The <em>she'er</em> (flesh) language grounds the prohibition in kinship: she shares your father's body, which makes her body an extension of your own family identity. The prohibition extends the incest boundary to the parental generation's siblings.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Mother's sister — the same reasoning. <em>Ki she'er immekha hi</em> (she is your mother's flesh). The symmetry between paternal and maternal prohibitions (vv. 12-13) ensures no distinction between the two lines of descent.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Father's brother's wife (aunt by marriage): you shall not approach his wife. <em>Dedat avikha hi</em> (she is your aunt) — the specific term <em>dodah</em> (aunt) appears here. The prohibition on the uncle's wife extends the sexual boundary to affinal (marriage-based) as well as consanguineal (blood-based) relationships.</p>",
    "15": "<p>Daughter-in-law: <em>eshet binekha hi</em> (she is your son's wife). <em>Lo tegalle ervatah</em> (you shall not uncover her nakedness) — this case is also mentioned in the Judah/Tamar narrative (Gen 38), where Judah unknowingly sleeps with his daughter-in-law. The Levitical prohibition makes what was transgressive in Genesis into an explicit legal offense.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Brother's wife. <em>Erva aḥikha hi</em> (it is your brother's nakedness) — parallel to the father-wife logic. The notable exception to this rule is the levirate law (Deut 25:5-10), which commands a man to marry his brother's widow when the brother died childless; Leviticus 18:16 prohibits this relationship in normal circumstances, while Deuteronomy creates a specific exception for line-preservation purposes.</p>",
    "17": "<p><strong>erva isha uvittah lo tegalle</strong>: 'You shall not uncover the nakedness of a woman and her daughter.' The prohibition on simultaneous relations with mother and daughter is absolute — <em>zimmah hi</em> (it is depravity). The term <em>zimmah</em> (depravity/wickedness) marks the most egregious violations within the sexual code. The prohibition extends to granddaughters in both directions.</p>",
    "18": "<p><strong>ve'isha el-aḥotah lo tiqqaḥ litsror</strong>: 'You shall not take a woman as a rival wife to her sister.' <em>Tsarah</em> (rival wife/adversary) is the technical term for a co-wife in a polygynous marriage. The prohibition applies only while both sisters are alive — <em>be'ḥayyeiha</em> (in her lifetime). This directly addresses the situation of Jacob's marriages to Leah and Rachel (Gen 29-30), who were biological sisters and produced the conflict that <em>tsarah</em> implies.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Sexual relations during menstruation (<em>niddah</em>). The prohibition connects the sexual laws with the broader purity system: menstruation generates ritual impurity (Lev 15:19-24), and sexual contact during that time compounds the impurity. The <em>niddah</em> category bridges the sexual ethics of ch. 18 and the bodily-discharge purity laws of ch. 15.</p>",
    "20": "<p><strong>ve'el-eshet amitekha lo titten shekhovtekha lezara</strong>: 'You shall not have sexual relations with your neighbor's wife, defiling yourself with her.' <em>Amitekha</em> (your neighbor/fellow Israelite) — the covenant community term. <em>Lezara</em> (for impurity/defilement) — the sexual violation is framed as a form of contamination parallel to ritual impurity. This is also the seventh commandment (<em>lo tin'af</em>, Exod 20:14), here given in its Levitical Holiness Code formulation.</p>",
    "21": "<p><strong>umiZar'akha lo-titten leha'avir laMolech</strong>: 'You shall not give any of your offspring to be offered to Molech.' <em>Molech</em> (also vocalized Molek) is the deity associated with child sacrifice, practiced in Canaan and apparently sometimes in Israel (2 Kgs 16:3; Jer 32:35). <em>Leha'avir</em> (to cause to pass through) is the technical term for child sacrifice in the OT. <strong>velo teḥallel et-shem Elohekha</strong>: 'do not profane the name of your God' — child sacrifice is framed as a desecration of YHWH's name, not merely a social atrocity. The insertion of the Molech prohibition within the sexual ethics code reflects its association with fertility-cult worship.</p>",
    "22": "<p><strong>ve'et-zakar lo tishkav mishkevei isha to'evah hi</strong>: 'You shall not lie with a male as with a woman; it is an abomination.' <em>To'evah</em> (abomination/detestable thing) is a strong term of categorical rejection, used elsewhere for idolatry (Deut 7:25) and child sacrifice (Deut 12:31). The verse prohibits male same-sex intercourse in terms drawn from the sexual categories of Lev 18 as a whole (<em>mishkevei isha</em>, literally 'lyings of a woman' = the manner of lying with a woman).</p>",
    "23": "<p><strong>uvekol-behema lo-titten shekhovtekha letame'ah bah</strong>: 'You shall not have sexual relations with any animal, defiling yourself with it.' <em>Tevel</em> (perversion/violation of created order) — the term used for bestiality; it conveys disorder at the level of creation categories, not merely moral transgression. The female parallel is explicit: a woman must not stand before an animal for sexual purposes. Both are <em>tevel</em> — violations of the created order of kinds.</p>",
    "24": "<p><strong>al-tittame'u bekhol-elleh</strong>: 'Do not defile yourselves by any of these things.' <em>Nitme'u</em> (became defiled) applies to the Canaanites — the land's former inhabitants who practiced these things and were expelled by YHWH. The defiling practices are not merely matters of cultural preference; they generated genuine moral-ritual impurity that affected the land itself.</p>",
    "25": "<p><strong>vatitma ha'arets vaeafqod avonah aleiha vataqqi ha'arets et-yoshveiha</strong>: 'The land became defiled; I punished it for its iniquity, and the land vomited out its inhabitants.' The land as a moral agent: <em>vataqqi</em> (vomited out) — the land cannot tolerate sustained moral pollution and expels its inhabitants. This is not mythological; it is the theological explanation of Canaanite displacement. The same threat is directed at Israel in v. 28 — the land has no ethnic loyalty; it vomits out whoever defiles it.</p>",
    "26": "<p>The obligation falls on Israel and on resident aliens (<em>hager hagar betokham</em>) equally — the sexual prohibitions are not merely Israel's cultural particularity but reflect moral norms applicable to all who live in the land. This extension to the alien is consistent with the Holiness Code's pattern of including non-Israelites in fundamental ethical obligations.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The Canaanites had committed all these abominations (<em>to'evot</em>) — hence their expulsion. The historical note grounds the prohibition in demonstrated moral-historical consequence: these practices bring divine judgment that results in national displacement. Israel is warned by precedent, not merely by abstract command.</p>",
    "28": "<p><strong>velo-taqqi ha'arets etkhem betam'akhem otah</strong>: 'Lest the land vomit you out when you defile it, as it vomited out the nation that was before you.' The land's moral intolerance is turned as a warning against Israel: identical behavior will bring identical consequences regardless of covenant status. The exile of 722 BCE (Israel) and 586 BCE (Judah) vindicated this warning — the land did indeed 'vomit out' Israel when it persisted in these practices.</p>",
    "29": "<p><strong>ki kol-asher ya'aseh mikkol-hatto'evot ha'elleh venikh'ru hanaefashot ha'osot</strong>: 'For anyone who commits any of these abominations — the persons who do them shall be cut off from among their people.' The <em>karet</em> penalty applies comprehensively across all the listed prohibitions. <em>Karet</em> (being cut off) in its most severe form may mean premature death at divine hands; in less severe applications it means exclusion from the covenant community.</p>",
    "30": "<p><strong>ushmartem et-mishmarti</strong>: 'Keep my charge.' <em>Mishmeret</em> (charge/obligation, what is kept/guarded) — the term for the covenant responsibility of obedience. The closing exhortation frames the entire chapter: Israel is to guard against the practices that caused Canaan's expulsion. <em>Ani YHWH Eloheikhem</em> — the opening refrain closes the chapter, forming an envelope structure around the entire sexual ethics code.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-original', 'leviticus')
    merge_comm(c, LEVITICUS)
    save_comm('mkt-original', 'leviticus', c)

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
